  <div class="topic">
    <h4>Positioning</h4>
    <p>If we go to the actual <a href="https://www.secrettelaviv.com/" target="_blank">Secret Tel Aviv</a> website, we'll notice that the navbar stays fixed to the top as we scroll. For that, we need to use <strong>position: fixed</strong>. Before we go over that though, let's look at the different options we have for positioing in CSS:</p>

    <h5>Absolute and Relative</h5>
    <p>Absolute positioning is tricky. The rule to remember is, <em>absolute positioned elements are position <strong>absolute</strong> in relation to their parent relative element</em>. Say what!? <a href="http://codepen.io/amhayslip/pen/ONJaJJ" target="_blank">Click here</a> for an example.</p>

    <p>We have the small green box the position of "absolute" and the large red box the position of relative. Thefore, the "absolute" positioned element (the green box) only obeys the red box (the relative positioned parent. We have it a "right: 0;" property, which puts it "0 away from the right side" of the red box.</p>

    <p>Now, remove the "position: relative" property from the ".large-box" and add it to the ".medium-box". What happened? Now the green box obeys the blue box.</p>

    <h5>Fixed</h5>
    <p>A "fixed" element works just like an absolutely positioned one, execept it's "relative parent" is the viewport. In other words, a fixed element stays fixed on screen no matter how much scrolling or whatever happens.</p>

    <p>Look at <a href="http://codepen.io/amhayslip/pen/aNbQOG" target="_blank">this example</a> here to see it in action. Notice how the red bar stays in it's place as your scroll.</p>

    <p>Okay, at last, let's position our nav to the top by adding the following CSS:</p>
    <pre style="background:#000;color:#f8f8f8"><span style="color:#cda869">nav</span> {
  <span style="color:#c5af75">background-color</span>: <span style="color:#dd7b3b">#333333</span>;
  <span style="color:#c5af75">position</span>: <span style="color:#f9ee98">fixed</span>;
  <span style="color:#c5af75">width</span>: <span style="color:#dd7b3b">100<span style="color:#e28964">%</span></span>;
  <span style="color:#c5af75">top</span>: <span style="color:#dd7b3b">0</span>;
}
</pre>
    
    <p>Also, let's center it and remove some unwanted margin:</p>
    <pre style="background:#000;color:#f8f8f8"><span style="color:#cda869">nav</span> <span style="color:#cda869">ul</span> {
  <span style="color:#c5af75">margin</span>: <span style="color:#dd7b3b">0</span>;
  <span style="color:#c5af75">text-align</span>: <span style="color:#f9ee98">center</span>;
}
</pre>
    
