  <div class="topic">
    <h4>CSS Box Model</h4>
    <p>At this point, your website should look like this:</p>
    <img src="http://www.elevationacademy.co/wp-content/uploads/2016/02/Screen-Shot-2016-02-29-at-11.19.19-AM.png">

    <p>We'll fix that, but let's first go over an important concept that we'll need to know before we dive in. The CSS Box Model.</p>

    <p>The “CSS Box Model” represents the way an element takes up space on the page. Namely, we’re referring to an element’s width/height, border, padding and margin properties. These things can dramatically the layout of a page and it’s important to know how it works.</p>

    <p><a href="http://codepen.io/amhayslip/pen/oxNKaY" target="_blank">Click here</a> to open an example we'll work with.</p>

    <p>Hover over the red box and, hold down "control", click and select "Inspect" (right click if you're using a windows machine). This will allow you to inspect the HTML and CSS of our webpage. If you look at the bottom of the "styles" tab, you'll notice a series of concentric boxes.</p>

    <img src="http://www.elevationacademy.co/wp-content/uploads/2016/02/Screen-Shot-2016-02-29-at-11.28.09-AM.png">

    <p>This is the box-model. It shows us that the width/height of the actual element is 200px, yet an extra 20px is added because of the padding and another 10 is added because of the border. Lastly, the margin doesn't actually add dimension to our element itself, but the space between it and other elements.</p>
