    <h5>Background Image</h5>
    <p>Before we add space above our image (to get it in the center of the screen), let's add our cool background image. For that we'll use the CSS Background Image property. Let's add it to our ".hero" section like this:</p>

    <pre style="background:#000;color:#f8f8f8"><span style="color:#9b703f">.hero</span> {
  <span style="color:#c5af75">background</span>: <span style="color:#dad085">url</span>(<span style="color:#3e87e3">http://www.elevationacademy.co/wp-content/uploads/2016/02/Tel-Aviv.jpg</span>) <span style="color:#f9ee98">no-repeat</span> <span style="color:#f9ee98">center</span> <span style="color:#f9ee98">fixed</span>;
  <span style="color:#c5af75">background</span>-<span style="color:#c5af75">size</span>: cover;
}
</pre>

    <p>A background-image can have a "background-repeat", "background-attachement" and "background-position" properties. We defined all of those, but with shorthand. In other words, we didn't want our image to repeat, we want it centered and fixed. In additon, we used "background-size: cover" to be sure that the entire image is displayed.</p>

    <p>In addition, we need to give our ".hero" section more height to look good. Let's give it a height of 700px:</p>

    <pre style="background:#000;color:#f8f8f8"><span style="color:#9b703f">.hero</span> {
  <span style="color:#c5af75">background</span>: <span style="color:#dad085">url</span>(<span style="color:#3e87e3">http://www.elevationacademy.co/wp-content/uploads/2016/02/Tel-Aviv.jpg</span>) <span style="color:#f9ee98">no-repeat</span> <span style="color:#f9ee98">center</span> <span style="color:#f9ee98">fixed</span>;
  <span style="color:#c5af75">background</span>-<span style="color:#c5af75">size</span>: cover;
  <span style="color:#c5af75">height</span>: <span style="color:#dd7b3b">700<span style="color:#e28964">px</span></span>;
}
</pre>

